{"title_page": "Circuit City", "text_new": "{{short description|Consumer electronics retailer}}\n{{about|the American company|the former Canadian division now owned by BCE|The Source (retailer)}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Circuit City Corporation\n| logo = CircuitCityComLogo.png\n| former_name = Wards Company {{small|(1949\u201384)}}<br>Circuit City Stores {{small|(1984\u20132009)}}\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = [[Retail]]\n| fate = Defunct as retail stores\n| predecessors = CircuitCity.com<br>[[TigerDirect]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1949|1|1}} (as Wards Company)<br>[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]<br>{{Start date and age|1984|1|1}} (as Circuit City)<br>{{Start date and age|April 2009}} (as CircuitCity.com)<br>2016 (as Circuit City Corporation, successor to the original and website)\n| defunct = {{End date and age|2009|3|9}} (as a retail)\n| founder = Samuel S. Wurtzel (original)<br>[[Systemax]] (website)<br>Ronny Shmoel (revival)\n| hq_location_city = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (when known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = [[Consumer electronics]]\n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (when known) -->\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (when known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (when known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (when known) -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (when known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (when known) -->\n| owner = Ronny Shmoel<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2016/01/28/circuit-city-is-back-from-the-dead-again.html</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (when known) -->\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|http://www.circuitcity.com/|circuitcity.com}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = <!-- Set positively (\"true\"/\"yes\"/etc) if company is international, otherwise omit -->\n| slogan = <!-- or: | slogans = -->\n}}\n\n'''Circuit City Corporation''' is an American [[consumer electronics]] [[retail]] company, established by Ronny Shmoel in 2016 as part of his acquisition of the brand name and trademark rights sold by [[Systemax]], which formerly operated the CircuitCity.com website from 2009 until 2012, when it was consolidated into the [[TigerDirect]] brand.\n\nFounded in 1949 by Samuel Wurtzel as the Wards Company, the original company operated stores across the United States and pioneered the electronics superstore format in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19930628&id=vlYzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jAcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6795,5280517|title=Circuit City plugged into future|first=Gregory|last=Gilligan|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=June 28, 1993|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref> After multiple purchases and a successful run on the NYSE, it changed its name to Circuit City Stores Inc.\n\n==History==\n===Early history and growth===\nIn early 1949 Wurtzel was on vacation in [[Richmond, Virginia]] when, while at a local barber shop, he was witness to the start of television in the [[Southern United States|South]].<ref name=\"encyclopedias\">{{cite web|title=Overview, Personal Life, Career Details, Chronology: Samuel Wurtzel Alan L. Wurtzel|url=http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6407/Wurtzel-Samuel-Wurtzel-Alan-L.html#ixzz4FloGQasP|website=Free Encyclopedias|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809042315/http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6407/Wurtzel-Samuel-Wurtzel-Alan-L.html#ixzz4FloGQasP|archive-date=August 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Imagining the opportunities, in late 1949, he moved his family to Richmond and opened the first Wards Company retail store.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Obituary: Samuel S. Wurtzel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/07/nyregion/samuel-s-wurtzel.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The New York Times|date=7 December 1985}}</ref> Later, Abraham L. Hecht joined him as a partner in the business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City: 2009 Going Out of Business Liquidation Sales, History, and Trivia|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/od/topusretailcompanies/p/circuitcitycorp.htm|website=About.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 1959, Wards Company operated four television and home appliance stores in Richmond. The company continued to grow and acquired stores in other locations including [[Albany, New York]]; [[Mobile, Alabama]]; [[Washington, D.C.]]; and [[Costa Mesa, California]]. During the 1970s and early 1980s, it also sold mail-order under the name \"Dixie Hi Fi\", advertising in hi-fi magazines. Wards experimented with several retail formats in Richmond, including smaller mall outlets branded \"Sight-n-Sound\" and \"Circuit City\".\n\n[[Image:Circuit City Superstore Original.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Original Circuit City Superstore format in [[San Antonio|San Antonio, Texas]]]]\nWards Company officially changed its name to Circuit City and became listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in 1984.<ref name=\"richmond\">{{cite news|last1=Janofsky|first1=Michael|title=Circuit City Takes a Spin At Used Car Marketing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/25/business/circuit-city-takes-a-spin-at-used-car-marketing.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The New York Times|date=25 October 1993}}</ref> One of the company's early slogans was \"Circuit City \u2014 Where the Streets are Paved with Bargains\". The company, which had leased floor space from the [[Zody's]] department stores as well as other department stores, began acquiring retail stores and turning them into Circuit City Superstores. The first of these replacements occurred in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]]; [[Charleston, South Carolina]]; and [[Hampton, Virginia]].\n\n[[Image:Circuit City.png|right|thumb|221px|Original Circuit City logo, used from 1984 to 1989.]]\nIn 1981, Circuit City entered the New York City market by acquiring the six remaining stores of the bankrupt [[Lafayette Radio]] chain.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rich Post|title=Sixty Years of Lafayette Radio|url=http://www.ohio.edu/people/postr/bapix/LafArt_60_3.htm|website=ohio.edu|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707020136/http://www.ohio.edu/people/postr/bapix/LafArt_60_3.htm|archive-date=July 7, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They operated the stores under the \"Lafayette/Circuit City\" name and expanded to 15 locations, but the stores were not profitable and were closed in 1986 after spending US$20 million to enter the market.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/history2/35/Circuit-City-Stores-Inc.html|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. \u2013 Company Profile, Information, Business Description, History, Background Information on Circuit City Stores, Inc.|date=|publisher=Reference for Business|accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref> Wurtzel served as president of the company until 1970. He remained the chairman until 1984.<ref name=obit/> When he stepped down, his son Alan served as chairman until 1994.<ref name=\"courier\">{{cite news|last1=Wise|first1=Warren|title=Circuit City closing|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20090117/PC05/301179952|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Post and Courier|date=17 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:CircuitCityLA.jpg|thumb|left|Variation on older \"Half Plug\" Circuit City Superstore format in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], using the \"Horizon\"-era logo.]]\n[[File:CircuitCityLogo2.PNG|thumb|left|The second Circuit City logo, used from 1989 to 2000. (continued to be used at some stores until 2009 liquidation)]]\n[[File:Circuit City Huntsville Ala.JPG|right|thumb|200px|\"Half Plug\" Circuit City Superstore format in [[Huntsville, Alabama]] that included a more open showroom, used from 1995 to 2000.]]\n[[File:Circuit City logo.svg|thumb|Third and final Circuit City logo, used from 2001 until its liquidation in 2009. (it was also used for the revival throughout its entire run until it shut down in 2012. A slightly modified version of this logo is used for the second revival.)]]\nWards purchased a new headquarters building at 2040 Thalbro Street (named after [[Thalhimers|Thalhimer Bros. Department Store]]) in Richmond, Virginia and in the extra space opened \"Wards Loading Dock\", its first big-box format in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orange.mync.com/site/orange/news/story/13428/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311071623/http://orange.mync.com/site/orange/news/story/13428|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 March 2016|title=Circuit City Files For Bankruptcy Protection|author=orange.mync.com|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref> The large-format store was very popular with customers. The company continued to expand with the new format modeled after \"Wards Loading Dock\" and renamed it Circuit City Superstore in 1981.<ref name=richmond/>\n\nIn 1988, the company began constructing the new \"plug\" design Superstore formats. During this era, Circuit City became known for its exceptional service, going so far as to have many of its staff factory-trained. Its slogan, likewise, was \"Welcome to Circuit City, Where Service Is State of the Art\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=Trexler Channel|title=Circuit City Dancing Dog commercial|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bH7cr2DLHMM|website=YouTube|accessdate=26 July 2016|date=28 July 2008}}</ref> Later, Circuit City returned to New York City opening a {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|abbr=on|adj=on}} superstore in [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]], the first of two planned Manhattan locations.<ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite news|author1=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|title=Circuit City to Grand Open First Manhattan Superstore|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/circuit-city-to-grand-open-first-manhattan-superstore-77061467.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=PR Newswire Association, LLC|date=20 October 1998}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n[[Image:Circuitcity.jpg|thumb|200px|Initial Horizon format in [[Rome, Georgia]], used in 2000]]\nBy 2000, many Circuit City stores were out of date and in bad locations, unable to compete with newer [[Best Buy]] stores. In 2000, Circuit City abandoned the large appliance business and introduced a more self-serve \"[[Big box retailer|Big Box]]\" format called \"Horizon\". This was controversial because in the previous year Circuit City was the second largest appliance retailer in the United States, behind only [[Sears]]. The company had earned nearly US$1.6 billion in sales revenue from large appliances in 1999. However, executives were concerned about the competition from [[Home Depot]] and [[Lowe's]] and believed there would be big savings in warehouse storage and delivery costs if they quit the large appliance business. It was later realized that Circuit City thus missed out on the [[United States housing bubble|residential housing boom of the mid-2000s]], which saw a dramatic rise in new-appliance sales.\n\n[[Image:Circuit City Denton TX.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Final Horizon format in [[Denton, Texas]], used from 2004 to 2007]]\n\nEvery Superstore was retrofitted after the exit from the large-appliance business, using the space for an expanded self-serve computer accessory and software selection. Stores at the time sold only PlayStation games under an exclusive agreement with [[Sony]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Cyrogenic|title=Circuit City|url=http://www.retrojunk.com/article/show/4946/circuit-city|website=Retro Junk|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> The new space allowed them to sell Nintendo, Sega, and eventually Xbox games after the agreement ended. Music and movie sales had been added to most stores years before, but the extra space allowed the selection to be added to smaller stores. The retrofitting project alone cost the company US$1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chandler|first1=Susan|title=Circuit City Abandons Appliances For Electronics|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-07-26/business/0007260497_1_circuit-city-stores-appliance-sears|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=26 July 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramstad|first1=Evan|title=Circuit City Unveils Plans to ExitAppliance Business, Take Charges|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB964528131640051432|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|date=26 July 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Circuit City converted to a single hourly pay structure in all stores, eliminating commissioned sales. Many previously commissioned sales associates were offered new positions as hourly \"product specialists\", while 3,900 salespeople were laid off, saving the company about $130 million per year. Many company insiders later revealed that they thought this was the most influential company decision that would ultimately lead to its demise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willis|first1=Barry|title=Cutbacks at Circuit City|url=http://www.stereophile.com/news/11569/#qHF10axCAxkvTQdm.97|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Stereophile|date=10 February 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Brandon|title=Circuit City Fires 3,400 \"Overpaid\" Employees|url=http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Fires+3400+Overpaid+Employees/article6691.htm|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Daily Tech|date=29 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052504/http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Fires+3400+Overpaid+Employees/article6691.htm|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, with the expansion of the [[Mobile phone|wireless phone]] market, Circuit City partnered with [[Verizon Wireless]] to include full-service Verizon Wireless sales and service centers in each Superstore. These locations were owned and staffed by Verizon Wireless. Circuit City stopped selling wireless phones with all other carriers due to the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hanford|first1=Desiree J.|title=Circuit City Stores Will Have Verizon Wireless Stores Inside|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB109386969858504439|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|date=30 August 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City and Verizon Wireless Expand Relationship; Plan to Launch New Store Concept|url=http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2004/08/pr2004-08-30a.html|website=Verizon Wireless News Center|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=29 August 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Circuit City announced its purchase of Canadian retailer [[InterTAN]]. Circuit City paid approximately US$284 million for InterTAN's 980 stores, which operated in Canada under the trade names [[RadioShack]], Rogers Plus, and Battery Plus. Chairman and CEO Alan McCollough believed these existing small-format stores provided an easy entry into Canada, a country where Best Buy had been expanding.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Barbara|title=Circuit City buys MusicNow service|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-04-01/business/0404010373_1_circuit-city-stores-online-music-industry-digital-audio-players|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=1 April 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Inc.|first1=Circuit City Stores|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Agrees to Acquire InterTAN, Inc. for $14 Per Share|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/circuit-city-stores-inc-agrees-to-acquire-intertan-inc-for-14-per-share-72276727.html|website=PRNNewsWire|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> RadioShack sued InterTan in April 2004 over the branding use of RadioShack in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Shack sues InterTan Inc.|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2004/04/05/daily19.html|website=Dallas Business Journal|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=6 April 2004}}</ref> Circuit City lost the lawsuit and all Canadian locations were renamed [[The Source (retailer)|The Source by Circuit City]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian RadioShack stores get new name|url=http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2005/04/27/radioshack-050427.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=CBC News|date=27 April 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212010217/http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2005/04/27/radioshack-050427.html|archivedate=February 12, 2007 }}</ref> These stores were sold to [[Bell Canada]] and continue to operate.\n\n[[File:Circuit_City_Torrington,_CT_(6935753191).jpg|thumb|256px|left|Circuit City's most recent store format nicknamed \"The City\", used from 2008 to 2009. Note the effects of a liquidation sale (including a \"store closing sale\" banner on the left) occurring on March 7, 2009 at [[Torrington, Connecticut]].]]\nIn 2007, a new {{convert|20000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} store format was introduced as \"The City\" and designed to eliminate previously under-utilized space. The smaller format gave the company greater flexibility to enter new markets and backfill existing ones. Most new store openings in 2008 used this new store format.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=Alan|title=Circuit's 'City' May Be Go-Forward Format For Chain|url=http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuits-city-may-be-go-forward-format-chain/6696|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Twice|date=7 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2007, Circuit City announced that it planned to close seven domestic Superstores and a Kentucky distribution center to cut costs and improve its financial performance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Announces Changes to Improve Financial Performance|url=http://newsroom.circuitcity.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=229136|website=Newsroom|publisher=Circuit City|accessdate=29 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070324201945/http://newsroom.circuitcity.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=229136|archivedate=March 24, 2007 |date=8 February 2008}}</ref> News reports also mention that 62 stores in Canada were to close.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Associated Press|title=Circuit City plans to close dozens of stores|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/feb/09/business/fi-circuit9|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=9 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nCircuit City announced on February 23, 2007 that its Chief Financial Officer, Michael Foss, would leave the company. This unsettled investors and analysts concerned about management turnover. \"This represents the third departure of a senior executive in the past six months, and the second departure of a top-five executive in the past month\" said Goldman Sachs analyst Matthew Fassler in a client note. Chief Executive Officer Phil Schoonover's \"hand-picked team is turning over faster than we would like to see in a turnaround situation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrell|first1=Andrew|title=Departure Of Foss Shocks Circuit City Investors - Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/02/26/foss-circuit-city-face-cx_af_0223autofacescan04.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Forbes|date=26 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the starting wage for new employees was dropped from $8.75 an hour down to $7.40 an hour ($6.55 being the federal minimum wage at the time). In a press release on March 28, 2007, Circuit City announced that in a \"wage management\" decision in order to cut costs, it had laid off approximately 3400 better-paid associates and would re-staff the positions at the lower market-based salaries. Laid-off associates were provided severance and offered a chance to be re-hired after ten weeks at prevailing wages. The ''Washington Post'' reported interviews with management concerning the firings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mui|first1=Ylan Q.|title=Circuit City Cuts 3,400 'Overpaid' Workers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/28/AR2007032802185.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=29 March 2007}}</ref> The ''Post'' later reported in May 2007 that the layoffs, and consequent loss of experienced sales staff, appeared to be \"backfiring\" and resulting in slower sales.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/01/AR2007050101623.html|title=Circuit City's Job Cuts Backfiring, Analysts Say |work=Washington Post |publisher=washingtonpost.com|date=2 May 2007|accessdate=28 October 2009|first=Amy|last=Joyce}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, video rental firm [[Blockbuster Inc.|Blockbuster]] announced a bid worth $1 billion to purchase Circuit City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blockbuster bids $1B for Circuit City|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=4652308|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=ABC News|date=14 April 2008|location=Dallas, Texas}}</ref> In July 2008, Blockbuster withdrew its offer due to market conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/afxnewslimited/feeds/afx/2008/07/01/afx5175198.html |title=Blockbuster withdraws proposal to acquire Circuit City |accessdate=1 July 2008 |work=Forbes |date=1 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705151450/http://www.forbes.com/afxnewslimited/feeds/afx/2008/07/01/afx5175198.html |archivedate=5 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, the chain's head office demanded stores destroy all copies of an issue of ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine which described \"Sucker City\" as a chain with a long list of locations, all in proximity to each other and each adjacent to a rival [[Best Buy]] store.<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City Orders All Stores To Destroy Issue Of Mad Magazine Parodying \"Sucker City\"|url=https://consumerist.com/2008/08/03/circuit-city-orders-all-stores-to-destroy-issue-of-mad-magazine-parodying-sucker-city/|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Consumerist|date=4 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nPhilip J. Schoonover, CEO, President and Chairman of the Board of Circuit City Stores, Inc. announced his immediate resignation on September 22, 2008. [[James A. Marcum]], former Vice Chairman of the board, was named acting CEO. [[Allen King]] was selected Chairman of the Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/management/personnel/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=210603329|title=informationweek.com|publisher=informationweek.com|date=September 23, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref>\nThis switch was said to be due to a stream of losses stemming from the rapid decline of flat-panel TV prices, and possibly due to the strong call for Schoonover's removal from [[activist shareholder]] Mark Wattles.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/C/db20080922_237728.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index+-+temp_companies businessweek] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n====Bankruptcy and liquidation====\n[[Image:CircuitCityBankruptcy.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Removal of signage on a former Circuit City store in [[Portland, Oregon]]]]\n[[File:2009-02-26 Circuit City going out of business.jpg|thumb|256px|right|A Circuit City store under the effects of a liquidation sale in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] on February 26, 2009.]]\nOn November 4, 2008, Circuit City announced that it would close 155 stores and lay off 17% of its workforce by the end of the year as a result of continuing difficulties in remaining profitable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Popken|first1=Ben|title=UPDATED: Breaking: Circuit City Closing 155 Stores|url=http://consumerist.com/5074161/breaking-circuit-city-closing-155-stores|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Consumerist|date=10 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081110163052/http://consumerist.com/5074161/breaking-circuit-city-closing-155-stores|archivedate=November 10, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Galuszka|first1=Peter|title=Eight Reasons Why Circuit City Went Bankrupt|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/eight-reasons-why-circuit-city-went-bankrupt/|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=CBS Money Watch|date=13 November 2008}}</ref> On November 7, 2008, Circuit City laid off between 500 and 800 corporate employees from its [[Richmond, Virginia]] headquarters. The approximately 1,000 remaining corporate employees were consolidated into one building in an effort to further reduce costs and improve profitability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginiabusiness.com/index.php/news/article/circuit-city-laying-off-headquarters-employees/114722/|title=Circuit City laying off headquarters employees|author=Llovio, Louis|date=November 7, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref> On November 10, 2008, Circuit City filed for bankruptcy protection under [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11]] of the United States Bankruptcy Code in the [[United States Bankruptcy Court]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia|Eastern District of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. - 3:08-bk-35653|url=https://www.pacermonitor.com/view/YBYW4PA/Circuit_City_Stores,_Inc.__vaebke-08-35653__0001.0.pdf|website=PacerMonitor|publisher=Virginia Eastern Bankruptcy Court|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Karen|title=Circuit City files for bankruptcy protection|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-circuitcity-idUSTRE4A936V20081110|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Reuters|date=10 November 2008}}</ref> At that time, Circuit City's stock traded well below $1 per share, and was removed from listing on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Statement Regarding NYSE Move to Delist Common Stock|url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2008111017530300004.pnw/topstory.html|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=News Blaze|date=10 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213220906/http://newsblaze.com/story/2008111017530300004.pnw/topstory.html|archivedate=February 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn bankruptcy court, Circuit City was approved to borrow $1.1 billion to finance operations while restructuring.<ref name=courier/> Court filings revealed that the company had assets of $3.4 billion and debt of $2.32 billion,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Files+Chapter+11/article13396.htm|title=dailytech|publisher=dailytech|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113113300/http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Files+Chapter+11/article13396.htm|archive-date=November 13, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> including a $119 million debt to [[Hewlett-Packard]] and a $116 million debt to [[Samsung|Samsung Electronics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=ayV.peP7hSAw&refer=home|title=bloomberg|publisher=bloomberg|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100321154128/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087|archive-date=March 21, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Chief executive James A. Marcum promised that the stores would stay open and the chain would not be liquidated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenbloom|first1=Stephanie|title=Circuit City Seeks Bankruptcy Protection|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/11/technology/11circuit.html?hp|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=The New York Times|date=10 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/10/AR2008111002931.html?hpid=sec-business|title=washingtonpost.com, Circuit City Files for Chapter 11 Protection|publisher=Washingtonpost.com|date=11 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009|first=Ylan Q.|last=Mui}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2008, it was announced that [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]], current owner of Mexican television broadcaster [[TV Azteca]] and electronics store chain [[Grupo Elektra|Elektra]], had purchased 28 percent of Circuit City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idUSTRE4AH7SQ20081118|title=Mexican tycoon Salinas sets eyes on Circuit City|agency=Reuters|date=18 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2009-02-26 Circuit City store closing everything must go.jpg|thumb|180px|Liquidation sale at Circuit City in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], in February 2009]]\nOn January 10, 2009, it was announced by a company spokesman that Circuit City needed a buyer by January 16, 2009 to keep from shutting its doors due to an approaching deadline set by the court and creditors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City needs buyer by next week|url=http://www.upi.com/Business_News/2009/01/10/Circuit_City_needs_buyer_by_next_week/UPI-50751231599658/|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=UPI|date=10 January 2009}}</ref> Although two unnamed parties were interested in buying out Circuit City,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peer|first1=Melinda|title=Circuit City Sparks Interest|url=https://www.forbes.com/markets/2009/01/10/circuit-city-buyer-markets-equity-cx_mp_0109markets40.html|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Forbes|date=10 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121214508/http://www.forbes.com/markets/2009/01/10/circuit-city-buyer-markets-equity-cx_mp_0109markets40.html|archivedate=January 21, 2009 }}</ref> a bidder could not be found,<ref name=\"Chris Bagley\">{{cite news|last1=Bagley|first1=Chris|title=Bankruptcy to kill 150 jobs at local Circuit City stores|url=http://nctimes.com/articles/2009/01/16/business/zf4a9e3ba60c777e588257540006218d9.txt|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=North County Times|date=16 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220103543/http://nctimes.com/articles/2009/01/16/business/zf4a9e3ba60c777e588257540006218d9.txt|archivedate=February 20, 2009 }}</ref> so Circuit City, with bankruptcy court approval, converted its Chapter 11 bankruptcy to Chapter 7,<ref name=\"Larry Yang\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianjournal.com/consumer/atty-larry-yang/1129-circuit-city-converts-to-chapter-7.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303091123/http://www.asianjournal.com/consumer/atty-larry-yang/1129-circuit-city-converts-to-chapter-7.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 3, 2009|title=Circuit City converts to Chapter 7|last=Yang|first=Lawrence|date=January 24, 2009|work=Asian Journal|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref> and started airing \"going out of business\" commercials, as they started closing all of their stores.<ref name=\"Chris Bagley\"/> The Canadian operations, which were run under [[The Source (retailer)|The Source by Circuit City]] banner, were not initially affected by the liquidation, but were later sold to [[Bell Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html |title=circuitcity.com |publisher=circuitcity.com |accessdate=October 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104075518/http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html |archivedate=January 4, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Circuit City's website, the company announced on January 16, 2009 that it intended to liquidate all of its stores. Reportedly, over 30,000 employees lost their jobs in the liquidation,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. to Liquidate|url=http://investor.circuitcity.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=359619|accessdate=15 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205011608/http://investor.circuitcity.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=359619|archivedate=February 5, 2009 |date=16 January 2009}}</ref> as well as 45% of Verizon's Circuit City sales force being laid off with the remainder resigning or transferring to other Verizon locations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fiercetelecom.com/story/update-verizon-wireless-lays-employees-formerly-circuit-city/2009-02-10|title=Update: Verizon Wireless lays off employees formerly at Circuit City|last=Wylie|first=Pete|date=February 10, 2009|publisher=Fierce Wireless|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe final day of operations for all Circuit City stores was March 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/b/2009/03/08/circuit-citys-final-sales-day-key-indicators-found-in-chapter-11-of-the-us-retail-industry-story.htm|title=Circuit City's Final Sales Day: Key Indicators Found in Chapter 11 of the U.S. Retail Industry Story|publisher=Retailindustry.about.com|date=|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Besides retail auto dealerships, Circuit City closed more retail locations in the U.S. than any other retail chain in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/od/statisticsresearch/a/storeclosings09.htm|title=2009 Retail Store Closings and Liquidations: Complete and Updated Ongoing List of Retailers Going Out of Business|publisher=Retailindustry.about.com|date=|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Circuit City selected Great American Group LLC, Hudson Capital Partners LLC, SB Capital Group LLC, and Tiger Capital Group LLC<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1873327,00.html|title=How Liquidators Profit from Circuit City's Loss|publisher=time.com|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> to handle the liquidation of all stores nationwide. Liquidation was completed on March 9, 2009.\n\nDuring the liquidation of all Circuit City stores across the nation, the company's online store was closed, and replaced it with a page that read as follows:<ref>{{cite web|title=Announcement|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html|publisher=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|accessdate=15 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227033519/http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html|archivedate=February 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text= Circuit City would like to thank all of the customers who have shopped with us over the past 60 years. Unfortunately, we announced on January 16, 2009, that we are going out of business.|author=Circuit City Stores, Inc., via its webpage}}\n\n===Revivals===\n[[Systemax|Systemax, Inc.]], in April 2009, signed a [[stalking horse]] agreement for $6.5 million, which was an initial offer for the bankrupt Circuit City's assets.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hylkmXHCI5Dhys7w7BU8I05-eNogD985DT100 Circuit City brand, Web site sold at auction \u2013 Associated Press \u2013 May 13, 2009] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2009, it was announced that Systemax had purchased the Circuit City brand name, trademarks, and e-commerce website for US$14 million at auction from Circuit City Stores, Inc. on May 11, with the deal set to take effect on May 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/|title=Accessed on May 20, 2009|publisher=Circuitcity.com|date=January 1, 1970|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>Video on Main Page on May 20, 2009 [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x9amco_circuitcitycom-announcement_tech dailymotion.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528055755/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x9amco_circuitcitycom-announcement_tech |date=May 28, 2009 }}</ref> Systemax relaunched the CircuitCity.com website on May 22, 2009, as an online retailer of consumer electronics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Systemax Announces Definitive Agreement to Acquire Selected Assets and Retail Stores From CompUSA|publisher=RedOrbit.com|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/technology/1205083/systemax_announces_definitive_agreement_to_acquire_selected_assets_and_retail/index.html?source=r_technology|accessdate=January 6, 2008|date=January 6, 2008}}</ref> Systemax had earlier acquired both [[CompUSA]] and [[TigerDirect]] separately, which superficially continued to operate as separate online retailers with the same website formats and product catalog along with the new CircuitCity.com site. The revived site's front page initially looked similar to the original front page, while other pages were similar in appearance and functionality to the other two sites.<ref>[http://www.dailytech.com/CircuitCitycom+is+Back+From+the+Dead/article15221.htm dailytech] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527111129/http://www.dailytech.com/CircuitCitycom+is+Back+From+the+Dead/article15221.htm |date=May 27, 2009 }} Accessed on May 25, 2009.</ref> All three sites eventually transitioned into slightly rebranded mirrors of each other.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nOn November 2, 2012, it was announced that Systemax would drop both the CompUSA and Circuit City storefront brands by consolidating their businesses under the TigerDirect brand and website. This ended, after 63 years, the use of the Circuit City brand name.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.twice.com/articletype/news/systemax-cut-circuit-city-compusa-brands-exit-pc-manufacturing/103788 |title=Systemax To Cut Circuit City, CompUSA Brands, Exit PC Manufacturing |publisher=Twice.com |date=2012-11-02 |accessdate=2013-11-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105061817/http://www.twice.com/articletype/news/systemax-cut-circuit-city-compusa-brands-exit-pc-manufacturing/103788 |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in January 2016 that the Circuit City brand would be revived as Circuit City Corporation by area retail veteran Ronny Shmoel, who acquired the brand from [[Systemax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuit-city-set-return-spring/60261|title=Circuit City Set To Return This Spring|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/01/28/circuit-city-is-back-from-the-dead-again.html|title=Circuit City is back from the dead, again - CNBC.com|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Circuit City was originally set to reopen in June 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuit-city-update-taking-our-time-get-it-right/61941|title=Circuit City Update: 'Taking Our Time To Get It Right'|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> but the postponed relaunch was announced at CES for February 15, 2018.<ref name=\"TwiceFeb18\">{{cite web|last1=Wolf|first1=Alan|title=Circuit City To Relaunch Feb. 15|url=https://www.twice.com/retailing/circuit-city-relauching-feb-15-website-stores-kiosks|website=Twice|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=9 January 2018}}</ref> On August 22, 2018, Circuit City Corporation officially relaunched the brand name as an online retailer and announced plans to begin operating as a [[store-within-a-store]] chain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dealerscope.com/article/in-time-for-black-friday-circuit-city-is-back-and-aiming-to-truly-differentiate/|title=In Time for Black Friday, Circuit City is Back and Aiming to Truly Differentiate - Dealerscope|last=Stott|first=Rob|work=Dealerscope|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Former subsidiaries==\n===CarMax===\n{{Main|CarMax}}\n[[File:2008-11-11 CarMax in Raleigh.jpg|left|200px|thumb|CarMax auto superstore in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]]]\n\n[[CarMax]] is a used car auto superstore concept developed in 1991 at Circuit City by [[Austin Ligon]], then Circuit City's Senior VP of Planning, and [[Richard Sharp (executive)|Rick Sharp]], then Circuit City CEO. The goal of CarMax was to revolutionize used car retailing through a combination of large selection (400+ used cars at each store); low, no-haggle pricing; guaranteed quality; and a consumer-friendly shopping experience. The first location opened in Richmond, Virginia in September 1993. [[CarMax]] grew slowly for its first four years as the team refined the basic concept, then went public through an IPO as a \"[[tracking stock]]\" ([[KMX]]) of Circuit City in February 1997. The offering was managed by Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs, and raised more than $400mm for a 20% interest in the company, with Circuit City retaining the remaining 80% ownership. [[CarMax]] used the proceeds to repay Circuit City's initial $170mm investment in the company, then used the remainder to grow rapidly, adding 27 more stores from 1997 to 2000, and turning its first profit in FY2001.<ref name=SEC>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-021911|title=CarMax|access-date=August 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429002644/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-021911|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Circuit City sold a further 10% of its interest in CarMax in July 2001 for $140mm, with proceeds going to Circuit City. CarMax was spun off from Circuit City in a tax free distribution to shareholders in October 2002 to allow both companies to grow and be valued independently. The stock distribution provided Circuit City shareholders with KMX stock valued at over $1.2bn at the time of the spin off in 2002.<ref name=SEC/>\n\n===Circuit City Express===\n'''Circuit City Express''' was a chain of mall-based Circuit City stores with over 55 locations at its peak. The first locations opened in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]]; [[Richmond, Virginia]]; and [[McLean, Virginia]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/circuit-city|title=Circuit City|author=answers.com|date=|accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref> The stores were originally called \"Impulse\", but were later renamed in 1993 to focus on the strength of the Circuit City brand. These stores focused on small electronic products for personal use or to be given as gifts. Cellular phones were a major focus of the business since all major carriers were sold until the exclusive agreement with Verizon Wireless in 2004. Circuit City Express stores offered Superstore prices and the Circuit City \"Price Match Guarantee\" in a mall environment. Most of the locations closed in the early 2000s as the original 10 year leases expired.\n\n===DIVX===\n{{Main|DIVX}}\n'''[[DIVX]]''' was developed by Circuit City and launched in 1997 as an alternative to DVD. DIVX discs cost $5 each, but could only be played for 48 hours on proprietary set-top players before a continuation fee was required to continue viewing. The player was connected to a phone line to check whether the disc was still valid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/125772-7/the_25_worst_tech_products_of_all_time.html|title=The 25 Worst Tech Products of All Time|author=pcworld.com|date=May 26, 2006|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> Opposition to the format and limited acceptance by the public led Circuit City to discontinue the format in 1999. Circuit City took a US$114 million loss to close its DIVX division.\n\n===Firedog===\n'''Firedog''' was launched in August 2006 to provide in-store, in-home, and online computer and [[home cinema|home theatre]] technical support and installation services<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?feed=AP&date=20090308&id=9675892|title=Timeline of Circuit City Stores Inc.|date=March 8, 2009|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in competition with other retailers' consumer and business technical services offerings such as [[Best Buy]]'s [[Geek Squad]] and [[Staples Inc.|Staples']] [[Staples Inc.#Staples EasyTech|EasyTech]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gogoi|first=Pallavi|url=http://www.businessweek.com/investor/content/aug2006/pi20060824_857413.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_businessweek+exclusives|title=Circuit City's Secret Service Plan|publisher=Businessweek.com|date=August 24, 2006|accessdate=October 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128030654/http://www.businessweek.com/investor/content/aug2006/pi20060824_857413.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_businessweek+exclusives|archivedate=January 28, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Firedog brand was sold to Firstmark for US$250,000 in September 2009, approximately six months after the liquidation of all Circuit City stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kamcity.com/namnews/asp/newsarticle.asp?newsid=49356|title=US: Circuit City Sells Online Assets|author=kamcity.com|date=September 2, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907125952/http://www.kamcity.com/namnews/asp/newsarticle.asp?newsid=49356|archivedate=September 7, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===First North American National Bank===\n'''First North American National Bank''' was created by Circuit City to operate its private-label credit card in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investor.circuitcity.com/history.cfm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928010834/http://investor.circuitcity.com/history.cfm|archivedate=September 28, 2007|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Company Timeline|date=September 28, 2007|publisher=[[Digital time capsule|Wayback Machine]] (originally on investor.circuitcity.com)|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref> In 2002, Circuit City began offering a co-branded [[Visa (company)|Visa]] credit card. It sold both of these operations in 2004 to [[Bank One]] (now [[Chase Bank]]).\n\n===Patapsco Designs===\n'''Patapsco Designs''' was acquired by Circuit City in 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2002/08/05/story7.html|title=Circuit City unit Patapsco lays off one-third of staff|last=Kady|first=Martin|date=August 2, 2002|publisher=Washington Business Journal|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref> The company was in charge of designing product displays and other electronic services for Circuit City. Patapsco Designs was founded in 1977 and is based in [[Frederick, Maryland]] and in November 2004 was acquired by American Computer Development Inc. Patapsco Designs, Inc. filed a voluntary petition for reorganization under Chapter 11 Bankruptcy in joint administration with Circuit City Stores, Inc. in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=9805458|title=Patapsco Designs, Inc.|author=businessweek.com|date=November 10, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Legal battles==\nIn 2004, [[RadioShack]] sued [[InterTAN]] to prematurely terminate its role as reseller for the Radio Shack line in Canada;<ref name=\"bizjournals.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2004/04/05/daily19.html|title=Radio Shack sues InterTan Inc.|work=Dallas Business Journal}}</ref>  the stores rebranded as \"[[The Source (retailer)|The Source]] by Circuit City\". In 2005, InterTAN sued RadioShack in an attempt to prevent it from re-entering the Canadian marketplace as a direct competitor;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twice.com/news/news/c-city-sues-radioshack/30380|title=C'City Sues RadioShack|work=twice.com|date=May 18, 2005}}</ref> while this effort failed, the nine new RadioShack-branded stores closed their doors by 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioshack.ca/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828210944/http://www.radioshack.ca/|title=Important information about RadioShack Canada|archivedate=August 28, 2008 |work=radioshack.ca}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Circuit City agreed to pay $173,220 in settlement and investigation reimbursement costs due to a false advertising claim in a 2004 [[New Jersey]] court case. The court found that important information pertaining to sale items was purposely obscured within the advertisement, thus potentially deceiving customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nj.gov/lps/newsreleases05/pr20051020a.html|title=New Jersey Office of the Attorney General|publisher=Nj.gov|date=October 20, 2005|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCircuit City's City Advantage Plan was also challenged in a [[United States District Court]] in [[Massachusetts]]. The plaintiffs' claim concerned Circuit City's cancellation of its [[warranty]] plan without full disclosure of the plan at the time of sale. The plaintiffs cited breach of contract, unjust enrichment, and violation of the Massachusetts Consumer Protection Act. Circuit City requested the matter be dismissed. The court, however, upheld the plaintiffs' claim that the monies paid for the protection plan be reimbursed and credit be issued for non-working goods returned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pacer.mad.uscourts.gov/dc/opinions/gorton/pdf/schacter.pdf|title=Schacter, and as representative for all persons similarly situated vs. Circuit City, Inc 05-12456-MNG|accessdate=October 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327052345/http://pacer.mad.uscourts.gov/dc/opinions/gorton/pdf/schacter.pdf|archivedate=March 27, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nLiquidators handling the sale of remaining Circuit City inventory have also become the target of consumer complaints, not only for often-uncompetitive pricing of items but also for an \"all sales final\" policy which allows the sale of defective or damaged merchandise at former Circuit City locations with no recourse afforded to the consumer.<ref>[http://www.thebostonchannel.com/asseenon5/18773855/detail.html Customers Burned In Circuit City Closeout Sale: No Recourse Offered For Damaged Items] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226200344/http://www.thebostonchannel.com/asseenon5/18773855/detail.html |date=February 26, 2009 }}, WCVB 5 Boston, February 23, 2009</ref>\n\n==Real estate holdings==\nDue to the expansion of Circuit City stores in the 1970s-1990s, the company accumulated a surplus of unused real estate with a presence in nearly every major market in the country. Although a typical retail location is approximately 30,000 square feet (2700 m\u00b2), the company had numerous freestanding and in-line locations ranging from 2,000 to 50,000 square feet (180 to 4500 m\u00b2), and had surplus office, service and distribution locations scattered across the country. During Circuit City's 2005 fiscal year (March 1, 2004 through February 28, 2005), the company disposed of approximately 1.2 million square feet (108,000 m\u00b2) of vacant retail space.<ref>[http://www.storetrax.com/CircuitCity/index.jsp storetrax.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610223154/http://www.storetrax.com/CircuitCity/index.jsp |date=June 10, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2007, Circuit City's vice president for real estate announced plans to open 200\u2013300 stores in the next two years, a large increase from the current trend of 10\u201312 stores a year.<ref>{{cite news|author=Parija B. Kavilanz, CNNMoney.com staff writer|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/01/15/news/companies/circuit.city/index.htm|title=Circuit City to roll out new prototype store \u2013 Jan. 15, 2007|publisher=Money.cnn.com|date=January 15, 2007|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Due to the economic conditions the company faced, they did not reach that goal. Many of these stores, however, did open in 2008 and operated for only a few weeks before closing. Some were built and never opened and upon the company's declaration of bankruptcy, it was discovered that large expenditures were due to paying leases on buildings that were not even opened to the public.\n\nIn January 2010, the main Circuit City headquarters building was put up for sale. The five-story {{convert|288650|sqft|m2|adj=on}} office building, \"Deep Run I\", had been appraised at $46.2 million. New York-based Lexington Property Trust, defaulted on a $17 million commercial mortgage and the lender foreclosed on the property. The asking price was set at $11 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2010/01/13/for-sale-circuit-city-headquarters/|title=For sale: Circuit City headquarters|publisher=Richmond BizSense|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=April 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2009/11/17/circuit-city-hq-returned-to-lender/|title=Circuit City HQ returned to lender|publisher=Richmond BizSense|date=November 17, 2009|accessdate=April 9, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125110222/http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2009/11/17/circuit-city-hq-returned-to-lender/|archivedate=November 25, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dcrealestate.citybizlist.com/yourCitybizNews/detail.aspx?id=64686|title=Citybizlist Washington, D.C. \u2013 former Circuit City HQ Up for Sale|publisher=Dcrealestate.citybizlist.com|date=|accessdate=April 9, 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The former headquarters was sold in September 2010, for $3 million to DRCC Properties, LLC. They also bought the {{convert|58|acre|m2}} of land that the building sits on for $2.75 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2010/09/17/circuit-city-hq-building-sold/ |title=Circuit City HQ building sold |publisher=Richmond BizSense |date=2010-09-17 |accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Best Buy]]\n*[[CompUSA]]\n*[[Good Guys (American electronics chain)|The Good Guys!]]\n*[[Tweeter (store)|Tweeter]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.circuitcity.com/ Circuit City Official Website]\n*[https://www.amazon.com/sp?seller=A3IRYX17GR1Q0K Circuit City @Amazon.com Storefront]\n*[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/circuit-city-stores-inc-history/ Circuit City Stores, Inc. History] at FundingUniverse\n\n[[Category:Circuit City| ]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics retailers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Companies that have filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2008]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2009 disestablishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Re-established companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Consumer electronics retailer}}\n{{about|the American company|the former Canadian division now owned by BCE|The Source (retailer)}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Circuit City Corporation\n| logo = CircuitCityComLogo.png\n| former_name = Wards Company {{small|(1949\u201384)}}<br>Circuit City Stores {{small|(1984\u20132009)}}\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = [[Retail]]\n| fate = Defunct as retail stores\n| predecessors = CircuitCity.com<br>[[TigerDirect]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1949|1|1}} (as Wards Company)<br>[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]<br>{{Start date and age|1984|1|1}} (as Circuit City)<br>{{Start date and age|April 2009}} (as CircuitCity.com)<br>2016 (as Circuit City Corporation, successor to the original and website)\n| defunct = {{End date and age|2009|3|9}} (as a retail)\n| founder = Samuel S. Wurtzel (original)<br>[[Systemax]] (website)<br>Ronny Shmoel (revival)\n| hq_location_city = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (when known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = [[Consumer electronics]]\n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (when known) -->\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (when known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (when known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (when known) -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (when known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (when known) -->\n| owner = Ronny Shmoel<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2016/01/28/circuit-city-is-back-from-the-dead-again.html</ref>\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (when known) -->\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|http://www.circuitcity.com/|circuitcity.com}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = <!-- Set positively (\"true\"/\"yes\"/etc) if company is international, otherwise omit -->\n| slogan = <!-- or: | slogans = -->\n}}\n\n'''Circuit City Corporation''' was an American [[consumer electronics]] [[retail]] company, established by Ronny Shmoel in 2016 as part of his acquisition of the brand name and trademark rights sold by [[Systemax]], which formerly operated the CircuitCity.com website from 2009 until 2012, when it was consolidated into the [[TigerDirect]] brand.\n\nFounded in 1949 by Samuel Wurtzel as the Wards Company, the original company operated stores across the United States and pioneered the electronics superstore format in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19930628&id=vlYzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jAcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6795,5280517|title=Circuit City plugged into future|first=Gregory|last=Gilligan|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=June 28, 1993|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref> After multiple purchases and a successful run on the NYSE, it changed its name to Circuit City Stores Inc.\n\n==History==\n===Early history and growth===\nIn early 1949 Wurtzel was on vacation in [[Richmond, Virginia]] when, while at a local barber shop, he was witness to the start of television in the [[Southern United States|South]].<ref name=\"encyclopedias\">{{cite web|title=Overview, Personal Life, Career Details, Chronology: Samuel Wurtzel Alan L. Wurtzel|url=http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6407/Wurtzel-Samuel-Wurtzel-Alan-L.html#ixzz4FloGQasP|website=Free Encyclopedias|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809042315/http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6407/Wurtzel-Samuel-Wurtzel-Alan-L.html#ixzz4FloGQasP|archive-date=August 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Imagining the opportunities, in late 1949, he moved his family to Richmond and opened the first Wards Company retail store.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Obituary: Samuel S. Wurtzel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/07/nyregion/samuel-s-wurtzel.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The New York Times|date=7 December 1985}}</ref> Later, Abraham L. Hecht joined him as a partner in the business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City: 2009 Going Out of Business Liquidation Sales, History, and Trivia|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/od/topusretailcompanies/p/circuitcitycorp.htm|website=About.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 1959, Wards Company operated four television and home appliance stores in Richmond. The company continued to grow and acquired stores in other locations including [[Albany, New York]]; [[Mobile, Alabama]]; [[Washington, D.C.]]; and [[Costa Mesa, California]]. During the 1970s and early 1980s, it also sold mail-order under the name \"Dixie Hi Fi\", advertising in hi-fi magazines. Wards experimented with several retail formats in Richmond, including smaller mall outlets branded \"Sight-n-Sound\" and \"Circuit City\".\n\n[[Image:Circuit City Superstore Original.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Original Circuit City Superstore format in [[San Antonio|San Antonio, Texas]]]]\nWards Company officially changed its name to Circuit City and became listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in 1984.<ref name=\"richmond\">{{cite news|last1=Janofsky|first1=Michael|title=Circuit City Takes a Spin At Used Car Marketing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/25/business/circuit-city-takes-a-spin-at-used-car-marketing.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The New York Times|date=25 October 1993}}</ref> One of the company's early slogans was \"Circuit City \u2014 Where the Streets are Paved with Bargains\". The company, which had leased floor space from the [[Zody's]] department stores as well as other department stores, began acquiring retail stores and turning them into Circuit City Superstores. The first of these replacements occurred in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]]; [[Charleston, South Carolina]]; and [[Hampton, Virginia]].\n\n[[Image:Circuit City.png|right|thumb|221px|Original Circuit City logo, used from 1984 to 1989.]]\nIn 1981, Circuit City entered the New York City market by acquiring the six remaining stores of the bankrupt [[Lafayette Radio]] chain.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rich Post|title=Sixty Years of Lafayette Radio|url=http://www.ohio.edu/people/postr/bapix/LafArt_60_3.htm|website=ohio.edu|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707020136/http://www.ohio.edu/people/postr/bapix/LafArt_60_3.htm|archive-date=July 7, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They operated the stores under the \"Lafayette/Circuit City\" name and expanded to 15 locations, but the stores were not profitable and were closed in 1986 after spending US$20 million to enter the market.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/history2/35/Circuit-City-Stores-Inc.html|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. \u2013 Company Profile, Information, Business Description, History, Background Information on Circuit City Stores, Inc.|date=|publisher=Reference for Business|accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref> Wurtzel served as president of the company until 1970. He remained the chairman until 1984.<ref name=obit/> When he stepped down, his son Alan served as chairman until 1994.<ref name=\"courier\">{{cite news|last1=Wise|first1=Warren|title=Circuit City closing|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20090117/PC05/301179952|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Post and Courier|date=17 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:CircuitCityLA.jpg|thumb|left|Variation on older \"Half Plug\" Circuit City Superstore format in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], using the \"Horizon\"-era logo.]]\n[[File:CircuitCityLogo2.PNG|thumb|left|The second Circuit City logo, used from 1989 to 2000. (continued to be used at some stores until 2009 liquidation)]]\n[[File:Circuit City Huntsville Ala.JPG|right|thumb|200px|\"Half Plug\" Circuit City Superstore format in [[Huntsville, Alabama]] that included a more open showroom, used from 1995 to 2000.]]\n[[File:Circuit City logo.svg|thumb|Third and final Circuit City logo, used from 2001 until its liquidation in 2009. (it was also used for the revival throughout its entire run until it shut down in 2012. A slightly modified version of this logo is used for the second revival.)]]\nWards purchased a new headquarters building at 2040 Thalbro Street (named after [[Thalhimers|Thalhimer Bros. Department Store]]) in Richmond, Virginia and in the extra space opened \"Wards Loading Dock\", its first big-box format in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orange.mync.com/site/orange/news/story/13428/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311071623/http://orange.mync.com/site/orange/news/story/13428|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 March 2016|title=Circuit City Files For Bankruptcy Protection|author=orange.mync.com|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref> The large-format store was very popular with customers. The company continued to expand with the new format modeled after \"Wards Loading Dock\" and renamed it Circuit City Superstore in 1981.<ref name=richmond/>\n\nIn 1988, the company began constructing the new \"plug\" design Superstore formats. During this era, Circuit City became known for its exceptional service, going so far as to have many of its staff factory-trained. Its slogan, likewise, was \"Welcome to Circuit City, Where Service Is State of the Art\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=Trexler Channel|title=Circuit City Dancing Dog commercial|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bH7cr2DLHMM|website=YouTube|accessdate=26 July 2016|date=28 July 2008}}</ref> Later, Circuit City returned to New York City opening a {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|abbr=on|adj=on}} superstore in [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]], the first of two planned Manhattan locations.<ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite news|author1=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|title=Circuit City to Grand Open First Manhattan Superstore|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/circuit-city-to-grand-open-first-manhattan-superstore-77061467.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=PR Newswire Association, LLC|date=20 October 1998}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n[[Image:Circuitcity.jpg|thumb|200px|Initial Horizon format in [[Rome, Georgia]], used in 2000]]\nBy 2000, many Circuit City stores were out of date and in bad locations, unable to compete with newer [[Best Buy]] stores. In 2000, Circuit City abandoned the large appliance business and introduced a more self-serve \"[[Big box retailer|Big Box]]\" format called \"Horizon\". This was controversial because in the previous year Circuit City was the second largest appliance retailer in the United States, behind only [[Sears]]. The company had earned nearly US$1.6 billion in sales revenue from large appliances in 1999. However, executives were concerned about the competition from [[Home Depot]] and [[Lowe's]] and believed there would be big savings in warehouse storage and delivery costs if they quit the large appliance business. It was later realized that Circuit City thus missed out on the [[United States housing bubble|residential housing boom of the mid-2000s]], which saw a dramatic rise in new-appliance sales.\n\n[[Image:Circuit City Denton TX.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Final Horizon format in [[Denton, Texas]], used from 2004 to 2007]]\n\nEvery Superstore was retrofitted after the exit from the large-appliance business, using the space for an expanded self-serve computer accessory and software selection. Stores at the time sold only PlayStation games under an exclusive agreement with [[Sony]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Cyrogenic|title=Circuit City|url=http://www.retrojunk.com/article/show/4946/circuit-city|website=Retro Junk|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> The new space allowed them to sell Nintendo, Sega, and eventually Xbox games after the agreement ended. Music and movie sales had been added to most stores years before, but the extra space allowed the selection to be added to smaller stores. The retrofitting project alone cost the company US$1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chandler|first1=Susan|title=Circuit City Abandons Appliances For Electronics|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-07-26/business/0007260497_1_circuit-city-stores-appliance-sears|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=26 July 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramstad|first1=Evan|title=Circuit City Unveils Plans to ExitAppliance Business, Take Charges|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB964528131640051432|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|date=26 July 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Circuit City converted to a single hourly pay structure in all stores, eliminating commissioned sales. Many previously commissioned sales associates were offered new positions as hourly \"product specialists\", while 3,900 salespeople were laid off, saving the company about $130 million per year. Many company insiders later revealed that they thought this was the most influential company decision that would ultimately lead to its demise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willis|first1=Barry|title=Cutbacks at Circuit City|url=http://www.stereophile.com/news/11569/#qHF10axCAxkvTQdm.97|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Stereophile|date=10 February 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Brandon|title=Circuit City Fires 3,400 \"Overpaid\" Employees|url=http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Fires+3400+Overpaid+Employees/article6691.htm|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Daily Tech|date=29 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920052504/http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Fires+3400+Overpaid+Employees/article6691.htm|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, with the expansion of the [[Mobile phone|wireless phone]] market, Circuit City partnered with [[Verizon Wireless]] to include full-service Verizon Wireless sales and service centers in each Superstore. These locations were owned and staffed by Verizon Wireless. Circuit City stopped selling wireless phones with all other carriers due to the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hanford|first1=Desiree J.|title=Circuit City Stores Will Have Verizon Wireless Stores Inside|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB109386969858504439|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|date=30 August 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City and Verizon Wireless Expand Relationship; Plan to Launch New Store Concept|url=http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2004/08/pr2004-08-30a.html|website=Verizon Wireless News Center|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=29 August 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Circuit City announced its purchase of Canadian retailer [[InterTAN]]. Circuit City paid approximately US$284 million for InterTAN's 980 stores, which operated in Canada under the trade names [[RadioShack]], Rogers Plus, and Battery Plus. Chairman and CEO Alan McCollough believed these existing small-format stores provided an easy entry into Canada, a country where Best Buy had been expanding.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Barbara|title=Circuit City buys MusicNow service|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2004-04-01/business/0404010373_1_circuit-city-stores-online-music-industry-digital-audio-players|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=1 April 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Inc.|first1=Circuit City Stores|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Agrees to Acquire InterTAN, Inc. for $14 Per Share|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/circuit-city-stores-inc-agrees-to-acquire-intertan-inc-for-14-per-share-72276727.html|website=PRNNewsWire|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> RadioShack sued InterTan in April 2004 over the branding use of RadioShack in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Shack sues InterTan Inc.|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2004/04/05/daily19.html|website=Dallas Business Journal|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=6 April 2004}}</ref> Circuit City lost the lawsuit and all Canadian locations were renamed [[The Source (retailer)|The Source by Circuit City]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian RadioShack stores get new name|url=http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2005/04/27/radioshack-050427.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=CBC News|date=27 April 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212010217/http://www.cbc.ca/money/story/2005/04/27/radioshack-050427.html|archivedate=February 12, 2007 }}</ref> These stores were sold to [[Bell Canada]] and continue to operate.\n\n[[File:Circuit_City_Torrington,_CT_(6935753191).jpg|thumb|256px|left|Circuit City's most recent store format nicknamed \"The City\", used from 2008 to 2009. Note the effects of a liquidation sale (including a \"store closing sale\" banner on the left) occurring on March 7, 2009 at [[Torrington, Connecticut]].]]\nIn 2007, a new {{convert|20000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} store format was introduced as \"The City\" and designed to eliminate previously under-utilized space. The smaller format gave the company greater flexibility to enter new markets and backfill existing ones. Most new store openings in 2008 used this new store format.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=Alan|title=Circuit's 'City' May Be Go-Forward Format For Chain|url=http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuits-city-may-be-go-forward-format-chain/6696|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Twice|date=7 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2007, Circuit City announced that it planned to close seven domestic Superstores and a Kentucky distribution center to cut costs and improve its financial performance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Announces Changes to Improve Financial Performance|url=http://newsroom.circuitcity.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=229136|website=Newsroom|publisher=Circuit City|accessdate=29 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070324201945/http://newsroom.circuitcity.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=229136|archivedate=March 24, 2007 |date=8 February 2008}}</ref> News reports also mention that 62 stores in Canada were to close.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Associated Press|title=Circuit City plans to close dozens of stores|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/feb/09/business/fi-circuit9|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=9 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nCircuit City announced on February 23, 2007 that its Chief Financial Officer, Michael Foss, would leave the company. This unsettled investors and analysts concerned about management turnover. \"This represents the third departure of a senior executive in the past six months, and the second departure of a top-five executive in the past month\" said Goldman Sachs analyst Matthew Fassler in a client note. Chief Executive Officer Phil Schoonover's \"hand-picked team is turning over faster than we would like to see in a turnaround situation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrell|first1=Andrew|title=Departure Of Foss Shocks Circuit City Investors - Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/02/26/foss-circuit-city-face-cx_af_0223autofacescan04.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Forbes|date=26 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the starting wage for new employees was dropped from $8.75 an hour down to $7.40 an hour ($6.55 being the federal minimum wage at the time). In a press release on March 28, 2007, Circuit City announced that in a \"wage management\" decision in order to cut costs, it had laid off approximately 3400 better-paid associates and would re-staff the positions at the lower market-based salaries. Laid-off associates were provided severance and offered a chance to be re-hired after ten weeks at prevailing wages. The ''Washington Post'' reported interviews with management concerning the firings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mui|first1=Ylan Q.|title=Circuit City Cuts 3,400 'Overpaid' Workers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/28/AR2007032802185.html|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=29 March 2007}}</ref> The ''Post'' later reported in May 2007 that the layoffs, and consequent loss of experienced sales staff, appeared to be \"backfiring\" and resulting in slower sales.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/01/AR2007050101623.html|title=Circuit City's Job Cuts Backfiring, Analysts Say |work=Washington Post |publisher=washingtonpost.com|date=2 May 2007|accessdate=28 October 2009|first=Amy|last=Joyce}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, video rental firm [[Blockbuster Inc.|Blockbuster]] announced a bid worth $1 billion to purchase Circuit City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blockbuster bids $1B for Circuit City|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=4652308|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=ABC News|date=14 April 2008|location=Dallas, Texas}}</ref> In July 2008, Blockbuster withdrew its offer due to market conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/afxnewslimited/feeds/afx/2008/07/01/afx5175198.html |title=Blockbuster withdraws proposal to acquire Circuit City |accessdate=1 July 2008 |work=Forbes |date=1 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705151450/http://www.forbes.com/afxnewslimited/feeds/afx/2008/07/01/afx5175198.html |archivedate=5 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, the chain's head office demanded stores destroy all copies of an issue of ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine which described \"Sucker City\" as a chain with a long list of locations, all in proximity to each other and each adjacent to a rival [[Best Buy]] store.<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City Orders All Stores To Destroy Issue Of Mad Magazine Parodying \"Sucker City\"|url=https://consumerist.com/2008/08/03/circuit-city-orders-all-stores-to-destroy-issue-of-mad-magazine-parodying-sucker-city/|accessdate=29 July 2016|work=Consumerist|date=4 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nPhilip J. Schoonover, CEO, President and Chairman of the Board of Circuit City Stores, Inc. announced his immediate resignation on September 22, 2008. [[James A. Marcum]], former Vice Chairman of the board, was named acting CEO. [[Allen King]] was selected Chairman of the Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/management/personnel/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=210603329|title=informationweek.com|publisher=informationweek.com|date=September 23, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref>\nThis switch was said to be due to a stream of losses stemming from the rapid decline of flat-panel TV prices, and possibly due to the strong call for Schoonover's removal from [[activist shareholder]] Mark Wattles.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/C/db20080922_237728.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index+-+temp_companies businessweek] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n====Bankruptcy and liquidation====\n[[Image:CircuitCityBankruptcy.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Removal of signage on a former Circuit City store in [[Portland, Oregon]]]]\n[[File:2009-02-26 Circuit City going out of business.jpg|thumb|256px|right|A Circuit City store under the effects of a liquidation sale in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] on February 26, 2009.]]\nOn November 4, 2008, Circuit City announced that it would close 155 stores and lay off 17% of its workforce by the end of the year as a result of continuing difficulties in remaining profitable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Popken|first1=Ben|title=UPDATED: Breaking: Circuit City Closing 155 Stores|url=http://consumerist.com/5074161/breaking-circuit-city-closing-155-stores|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Consumerist|date=10 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081110163052/http://consumerist.com/5074161/breaking-circuit-city-closing-155-stores|archivedate=November 10, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Galuszka|first1=Peter|title=Eight Reasons Why Circuit City Went Bankrupt|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/eight-reasons-why-circuit-city-went-bankrupt/|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=CBS Money Watch|date=13 November 2008}}</ref> On November 7, 2008, Circuit City laid off between 500 and 800 corporate employees from its [[Richmond, Virginia]] headquarters. The approximately 1,000 remaining corporate employees were consolidated into one building in an effort to further reduce costs and improve profitability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginiabusiness.com/index.php/news/article/circuit-city-laying-off-headquarters-employees/114722/|title=Circuit City laying off headquarters employees|author=Llovio, Louis|date=November 7, 2008|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref> On November 10, 2008, Circuit City filed for bankruptcy protection under [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11]] of the United States Bankruptcy Code in the [[United States Bankruptcy Court]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia|Eastern District of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. - 3:08-bk-35653|url=https://www.pacermonitor.com/view/YBYW4PA/Circuit_City_Stores,_Inc.__vaebke-08-35653__0001.0.pdf|website=PacerMonitor|publisher=Virginia Eastern Bankruptcy Court|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Karen|title=Circuit City files for bankruptcy protection|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-circuitcity-idUSTRE4A936V20081110|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Reuters|date=10 November 2008}}</ref> At that time, Circuit City's stock traded well below $1 per share, and was removed from listing on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Statement Regarding NYSE Move to Delist Common Stock|url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2008111017530300004.pnw/topstory.html|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=News Blaze|date=10 November 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213220906/http://newsblaze.com/story/2008111017530300004.pnw/topstory.html|archivedate=February 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn bankruptcy court, Circuit City was approved to borrow $1.1 billion to finance operations while restructuring.<ref name=courier/> Court filings revealed that the company had assets of $3.4 billion and debt of $2.32 billion,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Files+Chapter+11/article13396.htm|title=dailytech|publisher=dailytech|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113113300/http://www.dailytech.com/Circuit+City+Files+Chapter+11/article13396.htm|archive-date=November 13, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> including a $119 million debt to [[Hewlett-Packard]] and a $116 million debt to [[Samsung|Samsung Electronics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=ayV.peP7hSAw&refer=home|title=bloomberg|publisher=bloomberg|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100321154128/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087|archive-date=March 21, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Chief executive James A. Marcum promised that the stores would stay open and the chain would not be liquidated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenbloom|first1=Stephanie|title=Circuit City Seeks Bankruptcy Protection|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/11/technology/11circuit.html?hp|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=The New York Times|date=10 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/10/AR2008111002931.html?hpid=sec-business|title=washingtonpost.com, Circuit City Files for Chapter 11 Protection|publisher=Washingtonpost.com|date=11 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009|first=Ylan Q.|last=Mui}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2008, it was announced that [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]], current owner of Mexican television broadcaster [[TV Azteca]] and electronics store chain [[Grupo Elektra|Elektra]], had purchased 28 percent of Circuit City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idUSTRE4AH7SQ20081118|title=Mexican tycoon Salinas sets eyes on Circuit City|agency=Reuters|date=18 November 2008|accessdate=28 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2009-02-26 Circuit City store closing everything must go.jpg|thumb|180px|Liquidation sale at Circuit City in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], in February 2009]]\nOn January 10, 2009, it was announced by a company spokesman that Circuit City needed a buyer by January 16, 2009 to keep from shutting its doors due to an approaching deadline set by the court and creditors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Circuit City needs buyer by next week|url=http://www.upi.com/Business_News/2009/01/10/Circuit_City_needs_buyer_by_next_week/UPI-50751231599658/|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=UPI|date=10 January 2009}}</ref> Although two unnamed parties were interested in buying out Circuit City,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peer|first1=Melinda|title=Circuit City Sparks Interest|url=https://www.forbes.com/markets/2009/01/10/circuit-city-buyer-markets-equity-cx_mp_0109markets40.html|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=Forbes|date=10 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121214508/http://www.forbes.com/markets/2009/01/10/circuit-city-buyer-markets-equity-cx_mp_0109markets40.html|archivedate=January 21, 2009 }}</ref> a bidder could not be found,<ref name=\"Chris Bagley\">{{cite news|last1=Bagley|first1=Chris|title=Bankruptcy to kill 150 jobs at local Circuit City stores|url=http://nctimes.com/articles/2009/01/16/business/zf4a9e3ba60c777e588257540006218d9.txt|accessdate=15 August 2016|work=North County Times|date=16 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220103543/http://nctimes.com/articles/2009/01/16/business/zf4a9e3ba60c777e588257540006218d9.txt|archivedate=February 20, 2009 }}</ref> so Circuit City, with bankruptcy court approval, converted its Chapter 11 bankruptcy to Chapter 7,<ref name=\"Larry Yang\">{{cite news|url=http://www.asianjournal.com/consumer/atty-larry-yang/1129-circuit-city-converts-to-chapter-7.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303091123/http://www.asianjournal.com/consumer/atty-larry-yang/1129-circuit-city-converts-to-chapter-7.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 3, 2009|title=Circuit City converts to Chapter 7|last=Yang|first=Lawrence|date=January 24, 2009|work=Asian Journal|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref> and started airing \"going out of business\" commercials, as they started closing all of their stores.<ref name=\"Chris Bagley\"/> The Canadian operations, which were run under [[The Source (retailer)|The Source by Circuit City]] banner, were not initially affected by the liquidation, but were later sold to [[Bell Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html |title=circuitcity.com |publisher=circuitcity.com |accessdate=October 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104075518/http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html |archivedate=January 4, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Circuit City's website, the company announced on January 16, 2009 that it intended to liquidate all of its stores. Reportedly, over 30,000 employees lost their jobs in the liquidation,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. to Liquidate|url=http://investor.circuitcity.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=359619|accessdate=15 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205011608/http://investor.circuitcity.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=359619|archivedate=February 5, 2009 |date=16 January 2009}}</ref> as well as 45% of Verizon's Circuit City sales force being laid off with the remainder resigning or transferring to other Verizon locations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fiercetelecom.com/story/update-verizon-wireless-lays-employees-formerly-circuit-city/2009-02-10|title=Update: Verizon Wireless lays off employees formerly at Circuit City|last=Wylie|first=Pete|date=February 10, 2009|publisher=Fierce Wireless|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe final day of operations for all Circuit City stores was March 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/b/2009/03/08/circuit-citys-final-sales-day-key-indicators-found-in-chapter-11-of-the-us-retail-industry-story.htm|title=Circuit City's Final Sales Day: Key Indicators Found in Chapter 11 of the U.S. Retail Industry Story|publisher=Retailindustry.about.com|date=|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Besides retail auto dealerships, Circuit City closed more retail locations in the U.S. than any other retail chain in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retailindustry.about.com/od/statisticsresearch/a/storeclosings09.htm|title=2009 Retail Store Closings and Liquidations: Complete and Updated Ongoing List of Retailers Going Out of Business|publisher=Retailindustry.about.com|date=|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Circuit City selected Great American Group LLC, Hudson Capital Partners LLC, SB Capital Group LLC, and Tiger Capital Group LLC<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1873327,00.html|title=How Liquidators Profit from Circuit City's Loss|publisher=time.com|date=January 22, 2009|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> to handle the liquidation of all stores nationwide. Liquidation was completed on March 9, 2009.\n\nDuring the liquidation of all Circuit City stores across the nation, the company's online store was closed, and replaced it with a page that read as follows:<ref>{{cite web|title=Announcement|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html|publisher=Circuit City Stores, Inc.|accessdate=15 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227033519/http://www.circuitcity.com/closed.html|archivedate=February 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text= Circuit City would like to thank all of the customers who have shopped with us over the past 60 years. Unfortunately, we announced on January 16, 2009, that we are going out of business.|author=Circuit City Stores, Inc., via its webpage}}\n\n===Revivals===\n[[Systemax|Systemax, Inc.]], in April 2009, signed a [[stalking horse]] agreement for $6.5 million, which was an initial offer for the bankrupt Circuit City's assets.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hylkmXHCI5Dhys7w7BU8I05-eNogD985DT100 Circuit City brand, Web site sold at auction \u2013 Associated Press \u2013 May 13, 2009] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2009, it was announced that Systemax had purchased the Circuit City brand name, trademarks, and e-commerce website for US$14 million at auction from Circuit City Stores, Inc. on May 11, with the deal set to take effect on May 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.circuitcity.com/|title=Accessed on May 20, 2009|publisher=Circuitcity.com|date=January 1, 1970|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>Video on Main Page on May 20, 2009 [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x9amco_circuitcitycom-announcement_tech dailymotion.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528055755/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x9amco_circuitcitycom-announcement_tech |date=May 28, 2009 }}</ref> Systemax relaunched the CircuitCity.com website on May 22, 2009, as an online retailer of consumer electronics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Systemax Announces Definitive Agreement to Acquire Selected Assets and Retail Stores From CompUSA|publisher=RedOrbit.com|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/technology/1205083/systemax_announces_definitive_agreement_to_acquire_selected_assets_and_retail/index.html?source=r_technology|accessdate=January 6, 2008|date=January 6, 2008}}</ref> Systemax had earlier acquired both [[CompUSA]] and [[TigerDirect]] separately, which superficially continued to operate as separate online retailers with the same website formats and product catalog along with the new CircuitCity.com site. The revived site's front page initially looked similar to the original front page, while other pages were similar in appearance and functionality to the other two sites.<ref>[http://www.dailytech.com/CircuitCitycom+is+Back+From+the+Dead/article15221.htm dailytech] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527111129/http://www.dailytech.com/CircuitCitycom+is+Back+From+the+Dead/article15221.htm |date=May 27, 2009 }} Accessed on May 25, 2009.</ref> All three sites eventually transitioned into slightly rebranded mirrors of each other.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nOn November 2, 2012, it was announced that Systemax would drop both the CompUSA and Circuit City storefront brands by consolidating their businesses under the TigerDirect brand and website. This ended, after 63 years, the use of the Circuit City brand name.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.twice.com/articletype/news/systemax-cut-circuit-city-compusa-brands-exit-pc-manufacturing/103788 |title=Systemax To Cut Circuit City, CompUSA Brands, Exit PC Manufacturing |publisher=Twice.com |date=2012-11-02 |accessdate=2013-11-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105061817/http://www.twice.com/articletype/news/systemax-cut-circuit-city-compusa-brands-exit-pc-manufacturing/103788 |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in January 2016 that the Circuit City brand would be revived as Circuit City Corporation by area retail veteran Ronny Shmoel, who acquired the brand from [[Systemax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuit-city-set-return-spring/60261|title=Circuit City Set To Return This Spring|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/01/28/circuit-city-is-back-from-the-dead-again.html|title=Circuit City is back from the dead, again - CNBC.com|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Circuit City was originally set to reopen in June 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.twice.com/news/retail/circuit-city-update-taking-our-time-get-it-right/61941|title=Circuit City Update: 'Taking Our Time To Get It Right'|date=June 20, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> but the postponed relaunch was announced at CES for February 15, 2018.<ref name=\"TwiceFeb18\">{{cite web|last1=Wolf|first1=Alan|title=Circuit City To Relaunch Feb. 15|url=https://www.twice.com/retailing/circuit-city-relauching-feb-15-website-stores-kiosks|website=Twice|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=9 January 2018}}</ref> On August 22, 2018, Circuit City Corporation officially relaunched the brand name as an online retailer and announced plans to begin operating as a [[store-within-a-store]] chain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dealerscope.com/article/in-time-for-black-friday-circuit-city-is-back-and-aiming-to-truly-differentiate/|title=In Time for Black Friday, Circuit City is Back and Aiming to Truly Differentiate - Dealerscope|last=Stott|first=Rob|work=Dealerscope|access-date=2018-11-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Former subsidiaries==\n===CarMax===\n{{Main|CarMax}}\n[[File:2008-11-11 CarMax in Raleigh.jpg|left|200px|thumb|CarMax auto superstore in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]]]\n\n[[CarMax]] is a used car auto superstore concept developed in 1991 at Circuit City by [[Austin Ligon]], then Circuit City's Senior VP of Planning, and [[Richard Sharp (executive)|Rick Sharp]], then Circuit City CEO. The goal of CarMax was to revolutionize used car retailing through a combination of large selection (400+ used cars at each store); low, no-haggle pricing; guaranteed quality; and a consumer-friendly shopping experience. The first location opened in Richmond, Virginia in September 1993. [[CarMax]] grew slowly for its first four years as the team refined the basic concept, then went public through an IPO as a \"[[tracking stock]]\" ([[KMX]]) of Circuit City in February 1997. The offering was managed by Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs, and raised more than $400mm for a 20% interest in the company, with Circuit City retaining the remaining 80% ownership. [[CarMax]] used the proceeds to repay Circuit City's initial $170mm investment in the company, then used the remainder to grow rapidly, adding 27 more stores from 1997 to 2000, and turning its first profit in FY2001.<ref name=SEC>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-021911|title=CarMax|access-date=August 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429002644/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-021911|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Circuit City sold a further 10% of its interest in CarMax in July 2001 for $140mm, with proceeds going to Circuit City. CarMax was spun off from Circuit City in a tax free distribution to shareholders in October 2002 to allow both companies to grow and be valued independently. The stock distribution provided Circuit City shareholders with KMX stock valued at over $1.2bn at the time of the spin off in 2002.<ref name=SEC/>\n\n===Circuit City Express===\n'''Circuit City Express''' was a chain of mall-based Circuit City stores with over 55 locations at its peak. The first locations opened in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]]; [[Richmond, Virginia]]; and [[McLean, Virginia]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/circuit-city|title=Circuit City|author=answers.com|date=|accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref> The stores were originally called \"Impulse\", but were later renamed in 1993 to focus on the strength of the Circuit City brand. These stores focused on small electronic products for personal use or to be given as gifts. Cellular phones were a major focus of the business since all major carriers were sold until the exclusive agreement with Verizon Wireless in 2004. Circuit City Express stores offered Superstore prices and the Circuit City \"Price Match Guarantee\" in a mall environment. Most of the locations closed in the early 2000s as the original 10 year leases expired.\n\n===DIVX===\n{{Main|DIVX}}\n'''[[DIVX]]''' was developed by Circuit City and launched in 1997 as an alternative to DVD. DIVX discs cost $5 each, but could only be played for 48 hours on proprietary set-top players before a continuation fee was required to continue viewing. The player was connected to a phone line to check whether the disc was still valid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/125772-7/the_25_worst_tech_products_of_all_time.html|title=The 25 Worst Tech Products of All Time|author=pcworld.com|date=May 26, 2006|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref> Opposition to the format and limited acceptance by the public led Circuit City to discontinue the format in 1999. Circuit City took a US$114 million loss to close its DIVX division.\n\n===Firedog===\n'''Firedog''' was launched in August 2006 to provide in-store, in-home, and online computer and [[home cinema|home theatre]] technical support and installation services<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?feed=AP&date=20090308&id=9675892|title=Timeline of Circuit City Stores Inc.|date=March 8, 2009|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in competition with other retailers' consumer and business technical services offerings such as [[Best Buy]]'s [[Geek Squad]] and [[Staples Inc.|Staples']] [[Staples Inc.#Staples EasyTech|EasyTech]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gogoi|first=Pallavi|url=http://www.businessweek.com/investor/content/aug2006/pi20060824_857413.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_businessweek+exclusives|title=Circuit City's Secret Service Plan|publisher=Businessweek.com|date=August 24, 2006|accessdate=October 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128030654/http://www.businessweek.com/investor/content/aug2006/pi20060824_857413.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_businessweek+exclusives|archivedate=January 28, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Firedog brand was sold to Firstmark for US$250,000 in September 2009, approximately six months after the liquidation of all Circuit City stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kamcity.com/namnews/asp/newsarticle.asp?newsid=49356|title=US: Circuit City Sells Online Assets|author=kamcity.com|date=September 2, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907125952/http://www.kamcity.com/namnews/asp/newsarticle.asp?newsid=49356|archivedate=September 7, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===First North American National Bank===\n'''First North American National Bank''' was created by Circuit City to operate its private-label credit card in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investor.circuitcity.com/history.cfm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928010834/http://investor.circuitcity.com/history.cfm|archivedate=September 28, 2007|title=Circuit City Stores, Inc. Company Timeline|date=September 28, 2007|publisher=[[Digital time capsule|Wayback Machine]] (originally on investor.circuitcity.com)|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref> In 2002, Circuit City began offering a co-branded [[Visa (company)|Visa]] credit card. It sold both of these operations in 2004 to [[Bank One]] (now [[Chase Bank]]).\n\n===Patapsco Designs===\n'''Patapsco Designs''' was acquired by Circuit City in 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2002/08/05/story7.html|title=Circuit City unit Patapsco lays off one-third of staff|last=Kady|first=Martin|date=August 2, 2002|publisher=Washington Business Journal|accessdate=March 23, 2009}}</ref> The company was in charge of designing product displays and other electronic services for Circuit City. Patapsco Designs was founded in 1977 and is based in [[Frederick, Maryland]] and in November 2004 was acquired by American Computer Development Inc. Patapsco Designs, Inc. filed a voluntary petition for reorganization under Chapter 11 Bankruptcy in joint administration with Circuit City Stores, Inc. in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=9805458|title=Patapsco Designs, Inc.|author=businessweek.com|date=November 10, 2009|accessdate=November 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Legal battles==\nIn 2004, [[RadioShack]] sued [[InterTAN]] to prematurely terminate its role as reseller for the Radio Shack line in Canada;<ref name=\"bizjournals.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2004/04/05/daily19.html|title=Radio Shack sues InterTan Inc.|work=Dallas Business Journal}}</ref>  the stores rebranded as \"[[The Source (retailer)|The Source]] by Circuit City\". In 2005, InterTAN sued RadioShack in an attempt to prevent it from re-entering the Canadian marketplace as a direct competitor;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twice.com/news/news/c-city-sues-radioshack/30380|title=C'City Sues RadioShack|work=twice.com|date=May 18, 2005}}</ref> while this effort failed, the nine new RadioShack-branded stores closed their doors by 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioshack.ca/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828210944/http://www.radioshack.ca/|title=Important information about RadioShack Canada|archivedate=August 28, 2008 |work=radioshack.ca}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Circuit City agreed to pay $173,220 in settlement and investigation reimbursement costs due to a false advertising claim in a 2004 [[New Jersey]] court case. The court found that important information pertaining to sale items was purposely obscured within the advertisement, thus potentially deceiving customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nj.gov/lps/newsreleases05/pr20051020a.html|title=New Jersey Office of the Attorney General|publisher=Nj.gov|date=October 20, 2005|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCircuit City's City Advantage Plan was also challenged in a [[United States District Court]] in [[Massachusetts]]. The plaintiffs' claim concerned Circuit City's cancellation of its [[warranty]] plan without full disclosure of the plan at the time of sale. The plaintiffs cited breach of contract, unjust enrichment, and violation of the Massachusetts Consumer Protection Act. Circuit City requested the matter be dismissed. The court, however, upheld the plaintiffs' claim that the monies paid for the protection plan be reimbursed and credit be issued for non-working goods returned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pacer.mad.uscourts.gov/dc/opinions/gorton/pdf/schacter.pdf|title=Schacter, and as representative for all persons similarly situated vs. Circuit City, Inc 05-12456-MNG|accessdate=October 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327052345/http://pacer.mad.uscourts.gov/dc/opinions/gorton/pdf/schacter.pdf|archivedate=March 27, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nLiquidators handling the sale of remaining Circuit City inventory have also become the target of consumer complaints, not only for often-uncompetitive pricing of items but also for an \"all sales final\" policy which allows the sale of defective or damaged merchandise at former Circuit City locations with no recourse afforded to the consumer.<ref>[http://www.thebostonchannel.com/asseenon5/18773855/detail.html Customers Burned In Circuit City Closeout Sale: No Recourse Offered For Damaged Items] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226200344/http://www.thebostonchannel.com/asseenon5/18773855/detail.html |date=February 26, 2009 }}, WCVB 5 Boston, February 23, 2009</ref>\n\n==Real estate holdings==\nDue to the expansion of Circuit City stores in the 1970s-1990s, the company accumulated a surplus of unused real estate with a presence in nearly every major market in the country. Although a typical retail location is approximately 30,000 square feet (2700 m\u00b2), the company had numerous freestanding and in-line locations ranging from 2,000 to 50,000 square feet (180 to 4500 m\u00b2), and had surplus office, service and distribution locations scattered across the country. During Circuit City's 2005 fiscal year (March 1, 2004 through February 28, 2005), the company disposed of approximately 1.2 million square feet (108,000 m\u00b2) of vacant retail space.<ref>[http://www.storetrax.com/CircuitCity/index.jsp storetrax.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610223154/http://www.storetrax.com/CircuitCity/index.jsp |date=June 10, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2007, Circuit City's vice president for real estate announced plans to open 200\u2013300 stores in the next two years, a large increase from the current trend of 10\u201312 stores a year.<ref>{{cite news|author=Parija B. Kavilanz, CNNMoney.com staff writer|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/01/15/news/companies/circuit.city/index.htm|title=Circuit City to roll out new prototype store \u2013 Jan. 15, 2007|publisher=Money.cnn.com|date=January 15, 2007|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Due to the economic conditions the company faced, they did not reach that goal. Many of these stores, however, did open in 2008 and operated for only a few weeks before closing. Some were built and never opened and upon the company's declaration of bankruptcy, it was discovered that large expenditures were due to paying leases on buildings that were not even opened to the public.\n\nIn January 2010, the main Circuit City headquarters building was put up for sale. The five-story {{convert|288650|sqft|m2|adj=on}} office building, \"Deep Run I\", had been appraised at $46.2 million. New York-based Lexington Property Trust, defaulted on a $17 million commercial mortgage and the lender foreclosed on the property. The asking price was set at $11 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2010/01/13/for-sale-circuit-city-headquarters/|title=For sale: Circuit City headquarters|publisher=Richmond BizSense|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=April 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2009/11/17/circuit-city-hq-returned-to-lender/|title=Circuit City HQ returned to lender|publisher=Richmond BizSense|date=November 17, 2009|accessdate=April 9, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125110222/http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2009/11/17/circuit-city-hq-returned-to-lender/|archivedate=November 25, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dcrealestate.citybizlist.com/yourCitybizNews/detail.aspx?id=64686|title=Citybizlist Washington, D.C. \u2013 former Circuit City HQ Up for Sale|publisher=Dcrealestate.citybizlist.com|date=|accessdate=April 9, 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The former headquarters was sold in September 2010, for $3 million to DRCC Properties, LLC. They also bought the {{convert|58|acre|m2}} of land that the building sits on for $2.75 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondbizsense.com/2010/09/17/circuit-city-hq-building-sold/ |title=Circuit City HQ building sold |publisher=Richmond BizSense |date=2010-09-17 |accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Best Buy]]\n*[[CompUSA]]\n*[[Good Guys (American electronics chain)|The Good Guys!]]\n*[[Tweeter (store)|Tweeter]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.circuitcity.com/ Circuit City Official Website]\n*[https://www.amazon.com/sp?seller=A3IRYX17GR1Q0K Circuit City @Amazon.com Storefront]\n*[http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/circuit-city-stores-inc-history/ Circuit City Stores, Inc. History] at FundingUniverse\n\n[[Category:Circuit City| ]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics retailers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Companies that have filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2008]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2009 disestablishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Re-established companies]]\n", "name_user": "172.15.204.35", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit_City"}
